# Getting started with Kibana dashboards

This guide walks you through building a **web server log monitoring dashboard** with Terraform. You will add panels one at a time—markdown, KPI metrics, a time-series line chart, a horizontal bar chart, and a donut chart—using the [`elasticstack_kibana_dashboard`](/docs/resources/kibana_dashboard) resource and Kibana's built-in **sample logs** dataset.

Every visualization is defined **by value** in Terraform (no pre-existing saved objects required). Lens chart configuration is exported from the Kibana UI and embedded in `vis_config.by_value`; we explain that workflow explicitly so you can adapt the patterns to your own charts.

The runnable example lives at [`examples/guides/guide1-getting-started/main.tf`](https://github.com/elastic/terraform-provider-elasticstack/tree/main/examples/guides/guide1-getting-started/main.tf).

## Prerequisites

### Provider setup

Configure the Elasticstack provider with a Kibana connection. The example uses the default provider block (Kibana URL and credentials from environment variables or your usual provider configuration):

```terraform
terraform {
  required_providers {
    elasticstack = {
      source = "elastic/elasticstack"
    }
  }
}

provider "elasticstack" {
  kibana {}
}
```

See the [provider documentation](/docs/index) for authentication options (API keys, Elasticsearch credentials, Elastic Cloud, and `kibana_connection` overrides).

### Kibana version

These examples were tested against **Kibana 9.4+**. Lens panel JSON can change between minor versions; if a panel fails to render after upgrading Kibana, re-export the visualization from the UI (see [How to get Lens visualization JSON](#how-to-get-lens-visualization-json) below) and update the Terraform blocks.

### Install sample data

This dashboard queries the **`kibana_sample_data_logs`** data view. Install it once per Kibana space:

1. Open Kibana and go to the home page (or **Stack Management** → **Data** → **Sample Data**).
2. Under **Sample data sets**, find **Sample web logs** and click **Add data**.
3. Wait until Kibana reports the dataset as installed.

You do not need to create indices or ingest pipelines—the sample dataset ships with the field names used in this guide (`@timestamp`, `clientip`, `url.keyword`, `response.keyword`, and so on).

## Dashboard shell

Start with the dashboard resource itself: title, global time range, refresh behavior, and the default query language. These settings apply to every panel unless a panel overrides them.

```terraform
resource "elasticstack_kibana_dashboard" "getting_started" {
  title       = "Getting started: Web server logs"
  description = "A step-by-step web server log monitoring dashboard built with Terraform using Kibana sample logs data."

  time_range = {
    from = "now-7d"
    to   = "now"
  }

  refresh_interval = {
    pause = true
    value = 0
  }

  query = {
    language = "kql"
    text     = ""
  }

  panels = []
}
```

- **`time_range`** — Sets the dashboard's global time picker. Here we look at the last seven days (`now-7d` through `now`). Panels inherit this range unless they define their own `time_range`.
- **`refresh_interval`** — Controls auto-refresh. `pause = true` and `value = 0` mean the dashboard does not poll on a timer until a user enables refresh in the UI.
- **`query`** — The dashboard-level query bar. An empty `text` with `language = "kql"` means no global filter is applied; panels still respect any filters users add later.

Apply this configuration (with `panels = []` or before you add panels) and open the dashboard in Kibana. You should see the title, time picker, and an empty layout ready for panels.

![Dashboard shell with title and time range, no panels yet](images/g1-01-shell.png)

### The 48-column grid

Each entry in `panels` is positioned on Kibana's layout grid, which is **48 columns** wide. Use `grid` to place and size panels:

| Field | Meaning |
| --- | --- |
| `x` | Column offset from the left (0–47) |
| `y` | Row offset from the top (0-based) |
| `w` | Width in columns (1–48) |
| `h` | Height in row units |

Panels do not overlap: plan `x`, `y`, `w`, and `h` so each panel occupies a distinct rectangle. A full-width panel uses `w = 48`. Two side-by-side panels often use `w = 24` each.

```
 x=0          x=24         x=48
  ┌────────────┬────────────┐ y=0
  │            │            │
  │ panel A    │ panel B    │
  │ w=24, h=10 │ w=24, h=10 │
  │            │            │
  └────────────┴────────────┘ y=10
```

In the finished dashboard, the markdown header spans the full width (`w = 48`), the two metric panels sit on one row (`x = 0` and `x = 24`), and wider charts use the remaining vertical space.

Reuse a data view definition across Lens panels with a `locals` block so you do not repeat the same JSON:

```terraform
locals {
  logs_data_source = jsonencode({
    type          = "data_view_spec"
    index_pattern = "kibana_sample_data_logs"
    time_field    = "@timestamp"
  })
}
```

Set `data_source_json = local.logs_data_source` on each `metric_chart_config`, `xy_chart_config`, or `pie_chart_config` that reads from the sample logs.

> **By reference vs by value** — This guide uses only **by value** configs (`markdown_config.by_value`, `vis_config.by_value`, and so on) so `terraform apply` is self-contained. You can also reference existing saved visualizations with `by_reference` blocks; see the [`elasticstack_kibana_dashboard` resource reference](/docs/resources/kibana_dashboard) for that pattern.

## How to get Lens visualization JSON

Lens chart specs are not practical to write from scratch in Terraform. The supported workflow is to **prototype in Kibana**, then copy the serialized configuration into `vis_config.by_value`.

1. In Kibana, go to **Visualize Library** → **Create visualization** → **Lens** (or edit an existing Lens visualization).
2. Choose the **Sample web logs** data view and configure the chart (metrics, buckets, breakdowns) until it looks right.
3. Click **Inspect** (top right) → open the **Request** tab → select **Response**.
4. In the JSON response, find the saved-object **`attributes`** object. That structure is what Kibana stores for the visualization.
5. Map the relevant parts into the provider's typed blocks:
   - Count or single-number KPIs → `metric_chart_config` with `metrics[].config_json`
   - Line, area, or bar charts → `xy_chart_config` with `layers[]` (`type` = `line`, `bar_horizontal`, and so on)
   - Pie or donut → `pie_chart_config` with `metrics` and `group_by`
6. Fields that Kibana stores as nested JSON strings—`data_source`, axis domains, layer `x`/`y` operations—become `data_source_json`, `domain_json`, `x_json`, `config_json`, and similar attributes in Terraform. Wrap dynamic objects with **`jsonencode(...)`** so the provider receives valid JSON strings.

Re-export after Kibana upgrades if panels stop rendering or validation errors mention unknown Lens fields. The Terraform snippets in the following sections match exports taken from Kibana 9.4.

## Markdown panel

Add a full-width header panel that explains the dashboard. Markdown panels use `markdown_config.by_value` with `content`, `title`, and optional `settings`.

```terraform
{
  type = "markdown"
  grid = { x = 0, y = 0, w = 48, h = 6 }
  markdown_config = {
    by_value = {
      title   = "About this dashboard"
      content = <<-EOT
        # Welcome

        This dashboard monitors **web server logs** from the Kibana sample logs dataset.
        Explore request volume, top URLs, and HTTP response codes over the last 7 days.

        Learn more in the [Kibana dashboards guide](https://www.elastic.co/docs/explore-analyze/dashboards).
      EOT
      settings = {
        open_links_in_new_tab = true
      }
    }
  }
},
```

`content` accepts standard Markdown (headings, links, emphasis). Set `open_links_in_new_tab = true` so links open in a new browser tab instead of navigating away from the dashboard.

![Markdown panel across the top of the dashboard](images/g1-02-markdown.png)

## Lens Metric panels

Add two **Lens Metric** panels side by side: total event count and unique client IPs. Both use `vis_config.by_value.metric_chart_config`.

**Total events** (count):

```terraform
{
  type = "vis"
  grid = { x = 0, y = 6, w = 24, h = 10 }
  vis_config = {
    by_value = {
      metric_chart_config = {
        title                 = "Total events"
        data_source_json      = local.logs_data_source
        ignore_global_filters = false
        sampling              = 1
        query                 = { expression = "" }
        metrics = [{
          config_json = jsonencode({
            type      = "primary"
            operation = "count"
            format    = { type = "number" }
          })
        }]
      }
    }
  }
},
```

![First metric panel showing total event count](images/g1-03-metric1.png)

**Unique client IPs** (cardinality):

```terraform
{
  type = "vis"
  grid = { x = 24, y = 6, w = 24, h = 10 }
  vis_config = {
    by_value = {
      metric_chart_config = {
        title                 = "Unique client IPs"
        data_source_json      = local.logs_data_source
        ignore_global_filters = false
        sampling              = 1
        query                 = { expression = "" }
        metrics = [{
          config_json = jsonencode({
            type      = "primary"
            operation = "unique_count"
            field     = "clientip"
            format    = { type = "number" }
          })
        }]
      }
    }
  }
},
```

For cardinality, the provider expects **`operation = "unique_count"`** inside `config_json`, with the field name set on the same object (`field = "clientip"`). This mirrors Lens's unique-count metric in the UI; do not use a different operation name for the same chart type.

![Both metric panels in the KPI row](images/g1-04-metric2.png)

## Lens Line chart

Add a full-width **line chart** for request volume over time using `xy_chart_config`. The layer `type` is `line`; the X axis uses a date histogram on `@timestamp` and the Y axis uses a count operation.

```terraform
{
  type = "vis"
  grid = { x = 0, y = 16, w = 48, h = 14 }
  vis_config = {
    by_value = {
      xy_chart_config = {
        title = "Request volume over time"
        axis = {
          y = {
            domain_json = jsonencode({ type = "fit" })
            title       = { value = "Count", visible = true }
          }
          x = {
            title = { value = "@timestamp", visible = true }
          }
        }
        decorations = {}
        fitting     = { type = "none" }
        legend      = {}
        query       = { expression = "" }
        layers = [{
          type = "line"
          data_layer = {
            data_source_json = local.logs_data_source
            x_json = jsonencode({
              operation               = "date_histogram"
              field                   = "@timestamp"
              suggested_interval      = "auto"
              use_original_time_range = false
              include_empty_rows      = true
              drop_partial_intervals  = false
            })
            y = [{
              config_json = jsonencode({
                operation     = "count"
                empty_as_null = true
              })
            }]
          }
        }]
      }
    }
  }
},
```

The dashboard's global `time_range` drives which buckets appear; `suggested_interval = "auto"` lets Lens choose a reasonable histogram interval for the selected range.

![Line chart showing request volume over time](images/g1-05-line.png)

## Lens horizontal Bar chart

Add a **horizontal bar** chart for the top 10 URLs. This also uses `xy_chart_config`, but the layer `type` is **`bar_horizontal`**. The X dimension is a **terms** aggregation on `url.keyword` with `limit = 10`, sorted by the count metric descending via `rank_by`.

```terraform
{
  type = "vis"
  grid = { x = 0, y = 30, w = 24, h = 14 }
  vis_config = {
    by_value = {
      xy_chart_config = {
        title = "Top 10 URLs"
        axis = {
          y = { domain_json = jsonencode({ type = "fit" }) }
        }
        decorations = {
          minimum_bar_height = 1
          show_value_labels  = false
        }
        fitting = { type = "none" }
        legend  = {}
        query   = { expression = "" }
        layers = [{
          type = "bar_horizontal"
          data_layer = {
            data_source_json = local.logs_data_source
            x_json = jsonencode({
              operation = "terms"
              fields    = ["url.keyword"]
              limit     = 10
              rank_by = {
                type         = "metric"
                metric_index = 0
                direction    = "desc"
              }
            })
            y = [{
              config_json = jsonencode({
                operation     = "count"
                empty_as_null = true
              })
            }]
          }
        }]
      }
    }
  }
},
```

Use the `.keyword` subfield for terms aggregations on analyzed text fields. `rank_by` ties the terms order to metric index `0` (the count on `y`) in **descending** order so the longest bars are the highest-traffic URLs.

![Horizontal bar chart of top 10 URLs](images/g1-06-bar.png)

## Lens Donut chart

Finish with a **donut** chart of HTTP response codes using `pie_chart_config`. The metric is a count; `group_by` terms on `response.keyword`.

```terraform
{
  type = "vis"
  grid = { x = 24, y = 30, w = 24, h = 14 }
  vis_config = {
    by_value = {
      pie_chart_config = {
        title                 = "Response codes"
        donut_hole            = "s"
        label_position        = "outside"
        data_source_json      = local.logs_data_source
        ignore_global_filters = false
        sampling              = 1
        query                 = { expression = "" }
        metrics = [{
          config_json = jsonencode({
            operation = "count"
            format    = { type = "number" }
          })
        }]
        group_by = [{
          config_json = jsonencode({
            operation = "terms"
            fields    = ["response.keyword"]
            limit     = 10
            rank_by = {
              type         = "metric"
              metric_index = 0
              direction    = "desc"
            }
            color = {
              mode    = "categorical"
              palette = "default"
              mapping = []
            }
          })
        }]
      }
    }
  }
},
```

**`donut_hole`** controls the hole size (`"s"` small, `"m"` medium, `"l"` large in the schema). **`label_position = "outside"`** keeps slice labels readable on a dashboard tile.

